SCENARIO 1: Production Server Is Running Out of Space (SRE / Linux Admin)
Problem:

Monitoring alerts:

Disk usage / is above 85%

What You Would Do:
Step 1: Check which partition is full
df -h

Step 2: Find which directory is causing the issue
du -sh /* | sort -h

Step 3: Clean logs
rm -rf /var/log/*.gz
rm -rf /var/log/*-2023*

Step 4: Clean YUM cache
yum clean all
rm -rf /var/cache/yum

Step 5: Clear journal logs
journalctl --vacuum-size=100M

Real Output:

Disk space reduced from 91% â†’ 54%.

Interview Questions from This Scenario:

Q1: What log files usually grow large in Linux?
A: /var/log/messages, /var/log/secure, /var/log/audit/audit.log.

Q2: How do you find large files quickly?

find / -type f -size +500M


Q3: How do you trim journal logs?
A:

journalctl --vacuum-size=100M

ðŸŸ© ðŸŸ  SCENARIO 2: High CPU Usage on a Microservice (SRE / DevOps)
Problem:

A pod is running at 300% CPU and causing latency.

Step 1: Identify the problematic process
top

Step 2: If in Kubernetes â€” check pod CPU
kubectl top pods -n payments

Step 3: Check logs
kubectl logs payments-api-xyz -n payments

Step 4: Apply resource limits

Edit deployment:

resources:
  requests:
    cpu: 200m
  limits:
    cpu: 500m


Apply fix:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

Outcome:

CPU throttling stopped + app stable.

Interview Questions:

Q: What is CPU throttling?
A: When a pod hits its CPU limit, Kubernetes reduces CPU access.

Q: How do resource requests differ from limits?
A:

request = guaranteed minimum

limit = hard maximum

ðŸŸ© ðŸŸ¡ SCENARIO 3: Application Deployment Fails Due to Missing Dependencies (Linux Admin)
Problem:

Java app fails to start:

Error: libz.so.1 not found

Step 1: Find which package provides this file
yum provides */libz.so.1

Step 2: Install dependency
yum install zlib -y

Step 3: Restart the application
systemctl restart app.service

Interview Questions:

Q: How do you find which package provides a specific file?

yum provides /path/to/file


Q: What is the difference between yum install & rpm -ivh?

yum install resolves dependencies

rpm -ivh does NOT

ðŸŸ© ðŸŸ£ SCENARIO 4: SSH Access Broken After Firewall Rules Change

(Real scenario in many companies)

Problem:

No engineer is able to SSH into a production server.

Step 1: Connect via Console/Vcenter/AWS Session Manager

(No SSH available).

Step 2: Check firewall
firewall-cmd --list-all


Port 22 missing.

Step 3: Re-enable SSH
firewall-cmd --add-service=ssh --permanent
firewall-cmd --reload
systemctl restart sshd

Step 4: Verify
ss -tulnp | grep 22

Interview Questions:

Q: How do you check if SSH port is open?

ss -tulnp | grep ssh


Q: How do you fix firewall misconfiguration?
Use:

firewall-cmd --add-service=ssh

ðŸŸ© ðŸŸ¤ SCENARIO 5: Developers Unable to Pull Code from Git (DevOps)
Problem:

CI/CD pipeline is failing:

Permission denied (publickey)

Step 1: Check SSH key existence
ls ~/.ssh/id_rsa*

Step 2: Generate new key (if missing)
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096

Step 3: Add public key to GitHub
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub


Copy â†’ Add to GitHub â†’ SSH keys.

Step 4: Test
ssh -T git@github.com

Interview Questions:

Q: How do SSH keys work?
A: Public key stored on Git server â†’ private key on client.

Q: How do you test SSH connectivity?

ssh -vT git@github.com

ðŸŸ© ðŸ”´ SCENARIO 6: YUM Repos Are Not Working (Linux Admin / SRE)
Problem:
Cannot find valid baseurl for repo

Cause:

No DNS

No internet

Repo disabled

Fix Step 1: Check network
nmcli connection show
ping 8.8.8.8
ping google.com

Fix Step 2: Fix repo file
vi /etc/yum.repos.d/redhat.repo


Ensure:

enabled=1

Fix Step 3: Clean cache
yum clean all

Interview Questions:

Q: How do you check enabled repos?

yum repolist


Q: How to fix yum metadata issues?

yum clean all
rm -rf /var/cache/yum

ðŸŸ© ðŸŸ¦ SCENARIO 7: CI/CD Deployment Failed Due to Wrong YAML (DevOps)

Pipeline error:

Error: unable to parse deployment.yaml: mapping values are not allowed

Step 1: Validate YAML
yamllint deployment.yaml

Step 2: Fix indentation

Example error:

containers:
- name: app
image: nginx


Correct version:

containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx

Step 3: Re-run pipeline
Interview Questions:

Q: How do you validate YAML?
A:
yamllint file.yaml

Q: What is the most common YAML error?
A: Indentation.
